4.1 Error handling
==================

Functions in the Libmtx C library generally return a status code that
either indicates success (represented by the status code 'MTX_SUCCESS')
or a specific error.  Valid error codes correspond to values of the type
'enum mtxerror', which is defined in the file 'libmtx/error.h' along
with some error handling functions.

   The function 'mtxstrerror' can be used to give a string containing a
description of a given error code.

     const char * mtxstrerror(int err);

Here, the integer 'err' should correspond to one of the error codes from
the 'mtxerror' enum type.

   'mtxstrerror' is typically used as shown in the example below.

     struct mtxfile mtx;
     int64_t lines_read = 0;
     FILE * f = fopen("test.mtx", "r");
     int err = mtxfile_fread(
         &mtx, mtx_double, f,
         &lines_read, NULL, 0, NULL);
     if (err) {
         fprintf(stderr, "test.mtx:%d: %s\n",
                 lines_read+1, mtxstrerror(err));
         fclose(f);
     }

If 'mtxfile_fread' returns an error, for example,
'MTX_ERR_INVALID_MTX_OBJECT', then the following message will be
printed:

     test.mtx:1: invalid Matrix Market object


